body:
Node.js ESM (type: "module" in package.json) requires explicit file extensions in relative imports. CommonJS does not. This is the #1 migration pain point.

```javascript
// package.json: { "type": "module" }

// WRONG — works in CJS but fails in ESM
import { helper } from './utils';
// Error [ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND]: Cannot find module '/project/utils'

// CORRECT — must include .js extension
import { helper } from './utils.js';

// WRONG — directory imports don't work
import { config } from './config';
// Error: Cannot find module '/project/config'

// CORRECT — must reference the file
import { config } from './config/index.js';

// For TypeScript files compiled to JS:
// Source is utils.ts, but import must use .js
import { helper } from './utils.js'; // Resolves to utils.ts during compilation
```

Node.js ESM follows browser resolution rules — no automatic extension resolution and no directory index files. This is intentional and will not change.

`require()` is not defined in ES modules. Attempting to use it throws a ReferenceError. You must use `import` or create a require function manually.

```javascript
// package.json: { "type": "module" }

// WRONG
const fs = require('fs'); // ReferenceError: require is not defined

// CORRECT — use import
import fs from 'node:fs';
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';

// If you MUST use require in ESM (for CJS-only packages):
import { createRequire } from 'node:module';
const require = createRequire(import.meta.url);
const cjsPackage = require('some-cjs-only-package');

// For JSON imports in ESM:
// Option 1: createRequire
const pkg = require('./package.json');

// Option 2: import assertion (Node.js 22+)
import pkg from './package.json' with { type: 'json' };

// Option 3: fs.readFile
import { readFileSync } from 'node:fs';
const pkg2 = JSON.parse(readFileSync('./package.json', 'utf-8'));
```

Use `import` for everything in ESM. Use `createRequire` only as a last resort for CJS-only dependencies.

`__dirname` and `__filename` are CommonJS globals that don't exist in ES modules. Use `import.meta.url` instead.

```javascript
// CommonJS — these work
console.log(__dirname);  // /Users/app/src
console.log(__filename); // /Users/app/src/index.js

// ESM — these are undefined
// ReferenceError: __dirname is not defined

// Fix: derive from import.meta.url
import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url';
import { dirname, join } from 'node:path';

const __filename = fileURLToPath(import.meta.url);
const __dirname = dirname(__filename);

console.log(__dirname);  // /Users/app/src
console.log(__filename); // /Users/app/src/index.js

// For path resolution:
const configPath = join(__dirname, '..', 'config', 'app.json');

// Or use import.meta.dirname (Node.js 21.2+/22+)
console.log(import.meta.dirname);  // /Users/app/src — no utility needed!
console.log(import.meta.filename); // /Users/app/src/index.js
```

Node.js 21.2+ and 22+ provide `import.meta.dirname` and `import.meta.filename` as the clean replacement. For older versions, use the `fileURLToPath` approach.

Node.js 22's built-in `fetch()` (based on undici) does not throw on HTTP error status codes like 404 or 500. Only network errors throw.

```javascript
// WRONG — assumes fetch throws on 404
try {
  const data = await fetch('https://api.example.com/missing');
  console.log(await data.json()); // Tries to parse 404 HTML as JSON!
} catch (e) {
  // This catch does NOT fire for 404!
}

// CORRECT — check response.ok
const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/missing');
if (!response.ok) {
  throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`);
}
const data = await response.json();

// GOTCHA: response body must be consumed or the connection leaks
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
if (!res.ok) {
  // Must consume the body even on error!
  await res.text(); // or res.body?.cancel()
  throw new Error(`Failed: ${res.status}`);
}

// GOTCHA: fetch() does not support timeout natively
// Use AbortSignal.timeout() in Node.js 22
const controller = new AbortController();
const res2 = await fetch('https://slow-api.com/data', {
  signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5000), // 5 second timeout
});
```

Always check `response.ok` and always consume the response body. Use `AbortSignal.timeout()` for request timeouts.

Unlike some HTTP libraries (axios, ky), Node.js built-in fetch does not automatically serialize objects to JSON. You must stringify and set the Content-Type header manually.

```javascript
// WRONG — sends [object Object]
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/users', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: { name: 'Alice', age: 30 }, // Becomes "[object Object]"!
});

// CORRECT — stringify and set headers
const res2 = await fetch('https://api.example.com/users', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  body: JSON.stringify({ name: 'Alice', age: 30 }),
});

// For FormData, headers are set automatically:
const formData = new FormData();
formData.append('name', 'Alice');
formData.append('file', new Blob(['content']), 'file.txt');
const res3 = await fetch('https://api.example.com/upload', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: formData, // Content-Type: multipart/form-data set automatically
});

// GOTCHA: Response.json() throws if body is not valid JSON
try {
  const data = await res.json();
} catch (e) {
  // SyntaxError: Unexpected token < in JSON — probably got HTML error page
}
```

Always pair `JSON.stringify(body)` with `'Content-Type': 'application/json'`. The fetch API is low-level by design.

Worker threads in Node.js can share memory via `SharedArrayBuffer` but cannot share regular JavaScript objects. Objects passed via `postMessage` are cloned (serialized/deserialized), not shared.

```javascript
import { Worker, isMainThread, parentPort, workerData } from 'node:worker_threads';

if (isMainThread) {
  const shared = new SharedArrayBuffer(4);
  const view = new Int32Array(shared);
  view[0] = 42;

  const worker = new Worker(new URL(import.meta.url), {
    workerData: {
      shared,           // SharedArrayBuffer — truly shared memory
      regular: [1,2,3], // Regular array — cloned, not shared!
    },
  });

  worker.on('message', () => {
    console.log(view[0]); // 100 — worker modified shared memory!
  });
} else {
  const { shared, regular } = workerData;
  const view = new Int32Array(shared);
  view[0] = 100; // Modifies shared memory — visible to main thread

  regular.push(4); // Only modifies the clone — main thread won't see this!
  parentPort.postMessage('done');
}

// GOTCHA: Atomics needed for safe concurrent access
// Without Atomics, you get race conditions on SharedArrayBuffer
Atomics.store(view, 0, 100);     // Thread-safe write
const val = Atomics.load(view, 0); // Thread-safe read
Atomics.wait(view, 0, 100);       // Block until value changes
Atomics.notify(view, 0);          // Wake waiting threads
```

For complex data sharing between workers, serialize to SharedArrayBuffer with a protocol, or use MessageChannel for structured communication.

Readable streams in Node.js buffer data internally. If you create a stream but don't consume it (pipe or read), data accumulates in memory. Writable streams can signal backpressure that must be respected.

```javascript
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';

// WRONG — ignoring backpressure
const readable = createReadStream('large-file.csv');
const writable = createWriteStream('output.csv');

readable.on('data', (chunk) => {
  writable.write(chunk); // May return false if buffer is full!
  // Without checking, memory grows unbounded
});

// CORRECT — use pipe (handles backpressure automatically)
readable.pipe(writable);

// CORRECT — manual backpressure handling
readable.on('data', (chunk) => {
  const canContinue = writable.write(chunk);
  if (!canContinue) {
    readable.pause(); // Stop reading until writable drains
  }
});
writable.on('drain', () => {
  readable.resume(); // Writable buffer drained, continue reading
});

// GOTCHA: HTTP response is a readable stream — must consume it
import http from 'node:http';
http.get('http://example.com', (res) => {
  // If you don't consume res, the connection stays open!
  if (res.statusCode !== 200) {
    res.resume(); // Discard body to free up memory
    return;
  }
  // ... consume res
});

// Modern: use pipeline for proper error handling and cleanup
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
await pipeline(readable, transformStream, writable);
// Automatically destroys all streams on error
```

Always use `pipeline()` instead of `.pipe()` for proper error propagation and cleanup. Never ignore the return value of `.write()`.

`exec()` buffers the entire stdout/stderr in memory before returning, which can cause OOM for large outputs. `spawn()` streams output incrementally.

```javascript
import { exec, spawn } from 'node:child_process';
import { execFile } from 'node:child_process';

// DANGEROUS for large output — buffers everything in memory
exec('find / -type f', (error, stdout, stderr) => {
  // stdout could be hundreds of MB — OOM risk!
  // Default maxBuffer is 1MB (1024 * 1024)
  console.log(stdout);
});

// Error: maxBuffer length exceeded
// Fix: increase buffer (but still dangerous)
exec('find / -type f', { maxBuffer: 50 * 1024 * 1024 }, (err, stdout) => {});

// CORRECT — spawn streams output incrementally
const child = spawn('find', ['/', '-type', 'f']);
child.stdout.on('data', (chunk) => {
  // Process chunk by chunk — constant memory usage
  process.stdout.write(chunk);
});
child.stderr.on('data', (chunk) => {
  console.error('stderr:', chunk.toString());
});
child.on('close', (code) => {
  console.log('Exit code:', code);
});

// GOTCHA: exec() runs through shell (vulnerable to injection)
exec(`ls ${userInput}`); // DANGEROUS — shell injection!
// Fix: use execFile (no shell) or spawn with args array
execFile('ls', [userInput]); // Safe — no shell interpretation
spawn('ls', [userInput]);     // Safe — args are not shell-parsed
```

Use `spawn()` for long-running processes or large output. Use `execFile()` over `exec()` to avoid shell injection. Only use `exec()` for simple, trusted, small-output commands.

All environment variable values are strings. Comparisons with numbers or booleans fail silently because of JavaScript's type coercion.

```javascript
// .env: PORT=3000, DEBUG=false, MAX_RETRIES=5

// WRONG — comparing string to number
if (process.env.PORT === 3000) {
  // Never true! process.env.PORT is '3000' (string)
}

// WRONG — 'false' is truthy!
if (process.env.DEBUG) {
  // Always true if DEBUG is set! 'false' is a non-empty string = truthy
  console.log('Debug enabled'); // Runs even when DEBUG=false!
}

// CORRECT — explicit parsing
const port = parseInt(process.env.PORT || '3000', 10);
const debug = process.env.DEBUG === 'true';
const maxRetries = Number(process.env.MAX_RETRIES) || 5;

// GOTCHA: missing vars are undefined, not empty string
console.log(process.env.UNDEFINED_VAR); // undefined
console.log(process.env.UNDEFINED_VAR || 'default'); // 'default'

// Node.js 22 --env-file flag for loading .env files
// node --env-file=.env app.js
// Loads .env automatically — no dotenv package needed!

// But still all values are strings:
// .env: FEATURE_FLAG=true
// process.env.FEATURE_FLAG === 'true' // true (string comparison)
```

Always explicitly parse env vars to the correct type. Use `=== 'true'` for booleans, `parseInt/Number` for numbers. Consider using Zod's `z.coerce` for validation.

Node.js 22's `--env-file` flag loads `.env` files but does NOT override variables that already exist in the environment. This differs from some dotenv configurations.

```bash
# .env file
PORT=3000
DATABASE_URL=postgres://localhost/mydb

# If PORT is already set in the environment:
export PORT=8080
node --env-file=.env app.js
# process.env.PORT is '8080' — NOT overridden by .env!

# To load multiple env files (later files don't override earlier ones):
node --env-file=.env --env-file=.env.local app.js

# .env.local variables only apply if not already set by .env or environment
```

```javascript
// In your app:
console.log(process.env.PORT); // '8080' if set in environment, '3000' from .env otherwise

// GOTCHA: --env-file does not support:
// - Variable expansion: DATABASE_URL=postgres://${DB_HOST}/mydb
// - Multi-line values (use \n in single line)
// - Export prefix: export PORT=3000 (treated as part of value)
// - Comments must be on their own line (# comment) not inline

// For variable expansion, you still need dotenv:
import 'dotenv/config'; // supports ${VAR} expansion
import { expand } from 'dotenv-expand';
```

The `--env-file` flag is a simple key=value loader. For advanced features like variable expansion, continue using the dotenv package.

The `fs/promises` API operates independently from synchronous `fs` methods. Mixing them can lead to unexpected behavior with file handles and race conditions.

```javascript
import { open, readFile, writeFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
import { readFileSync, writeFileSync } from 'node:fs';

// GOTCHA: async and sync operations can interleave
async function riskyOperation() {
  // Start async write
  const writePromise = writeFile('data.json', JSON.stringify({ version: 2 }));

  // Sync read happens DURING async write — may get partial data!
  const data = readFileSync('data.json', 'utf-8');
  // data could be corrupt/partial

  await writePromise;
}

// CORRECT: use all async
async function safeOperation() {
  await writeFile('data.json', JSON.stringify({ version: 2 }));
  const data = await readFile('data.json', 'utf-8');
}

// GOTCHA: file handles must be closed
const handle = await open('data.log', 'a');
try {
  await handle.write('log entry\n');
  await handle.write('another entry\n');
} finally {
  await handle.close(); // MUST close or file descriptor leaks!
}

// Modern: use using (explicit resource management, Node.js 22+)
// Requires --harmony-explicit-resource-management or TypeScript 5.2+
await using handle2 = await open('data.log', 'a');
await handle2.write('log entry\n');
// handle2 automatically closed when block exits
```

Never mix sync and async file operations on the same file. Always close file handles in a `finally` block.

Unlike browsers where `crypto.subtle` is available globally, in Node.js you need to import it from the `node:crypto` module, and some operations differ from the Web Crypto API.

```javascript
// WRONG — doesn't work in Node.js (unless using globalThis.crypto)
crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', data);
// ReferenceError or TypeError depending on Node version

// CORRECT — import from node:crypto
import { webcrypto } from 'node:crypto';
const { subtle } = webcrypto;

// Or in Node.js 22+, globalThis.crypto is available:
const hash = await globalThis.crypto.subtle.digest(
  'SHA-256',
  new TextEncoder().encode('hello')
);

// GOTCHA: crypto.subtle only works with specific key formats
// For simple hashing, the traditional API is simpler:
import { createHash, createHmac } from 'node:crypto';

const hash2 = createHash('sha256').update('hello').digest('hex');
// '2cf24dba5fb0a30e26e83b2ac5b9e29e1b161e5c1fa7425e73043362938b9824'

// GOTCHA: subtle.importKey requires specific formats
const key = await subtle.importKey(
  'raw',
  new TextEncoder().encode('my-secret-key-32-bytes-long!!!!'),
  { name: 'AES-GCM' },
  false,
  ['encrypt', 'decrypt']
);

// For most Node.js use cases, use node:crypto directly
// subtle is mainly for code shared between browser and Node
```

Use `node:crypto` functions for server-side code. Use `crypto.subtle` only when you need browser-compatible crypto code.

Node.js HTTP/2 uses a completely different module (`node:http2`) with different APIs. You cannot use `http.createServer` for HTTP/2.

```javascript
import http2 from 'node:http2';
import { readFileSync } from 'node:fs';

// HTTP/2 requires TLS in browsers (h2), but Node supports cleartext (h2c)

// Secure HTTP/2 server
const server = http2.createSecureServer({
  key: readFileSync('server.key'),
  cert: readFileSync('server.crt'),
});

server.on('stream', (stream, headers) => {
  // GOTCHA: no req/res objects — uses streams and headers
  const path = headers[':path'];
  const method = headers[':method'];

  stream.respond({
    ':status': 200,
    'content-type': 'application/json',
  });
  stream.end(JSON.stringify({ path, method }));
});

// Compatibility API (looks like http1, easier migration)
const compatServer = http2.createSecureServer({
  key: readFileSync('server.key'),
  cert: readFileSync('server.crt'),
  allowHTTP1: true, // Fall back to HTTP/1.1 for older clients
});

compatServer.on('request', (req, res) => {
  // req and res look like http1 — but support HTTP/2 features
  res.writeHead(200);
  res.end('Hello');
});

// GOTCHA: HTTP/2 client is different too
const client = http2.connect('https://example.com');
const req = client.request({ ':path': '/api/data' });
let data = '';
req.on('data', chunk => data += chunk);
req.on('end', () => {
  console.log(data);
  client.close(); // Must close the session!
});
```

Use the compatibility API (`allowHTTP1: true`) for gradual migration. Most frameworks (Express, Fastify) handle HTTP/2 transparently.

The `exports` field in package.json restricts which files can be imported from your package. Files not listed in `exports` are inaccessible to consumers, even if they exist.

```json
{
  "name": "my-lib",
  "type": "module",
  "exports": {
    ".": {
      "types": "./dist/index.d.ts",
      "import": "./dist/index.mjs",
      "require": "./dist/index.cjs",
      "default": "./dist/index.mjs"
    },
    "./utils": {
      "types": "./dist/utils.d.ts",
      "import": "./dist/utils.mjs",
      "require": "./dist/utils.cjs"
    }
  }
}
```

```javascript
// These work:
import { foo } from 'my-lib';       // Maps to ./dist/index.mjs
import { bar } from 'my-lib/utils'; // Maps to ./dist/utils.mjs

// These FAIL even though files exist:
import { internal } from 'my-lib/dist/internal.mjs';
// Error [ERR_PACKAGE_PATH_NOT_EXPORTED]: Package subpath './dist/internal.mjs' is not defined by "exports"

// GOTCHA: exports overrides main field completely
// If exports is defined, main is ignored for ESM

// GOTCHA: condition order matters — first match wins
// "types" must come before "import"/"require" for TypeScript

// GOTCHA: wildcard exports
"exports": {
  "./components/*": "./dist/components/*.js"
}
// import { Button } from 'my-lib/components/Button'
```

The `types` condition must be listed first. Always test both `import` and `require` entry points. The `exports` field is the modern replacement for `main`.

Node.js 22's experimental permission model (`--experimental-permission`) restricts the main process but child processes inherit permissions and can bypass restrictions.

```bash
# Run with restricted file system access
node --experimental-permission --allow-fs-read=/app/data app.js

# The main process can only read from /app/data
# But...
```

```javascript
import { execSync } from 'node:child_process';

// GOTCHA: child process can access anything!
// Unless --allow-child-process is NOT granted
try {
  // Error: Access to this API has been restricted
  execSync('cat /etc/passwd');
} catch (e) {
  console.log(e.message); // Permission denied if --allow-child-process not set
}

// Permission flags:
// --allow-fs-read=<path>  — restrict file reads
// --allow-fs-write=<path> — restrict file writes
// --allow-child-process   — allow spawning child processes
// --allow-worker          — allow worker threads

// GOTCHA: must explicitly allow each resource
// node --experimental-permission app.js
// Without ANY --allow flags, almost everything is blocked!

// Check permissions at runtime:
import { permission } from 'node:process';
if (permission.has('fs.read', '/app/data')) {
  // Can read /app/data
}
if (!permission.has('child')) {
  console.log('Cannot spawn child processes');
}
```

The permission model is still experimental. It provides defense in depth but is not a security sandbox. Always combine with OS-level sandboxing for production security.

Node.js 22's built-in test runner uses `node:assert` for assertions, not the `expect()` syntax familiar from Jest or Vitest. The API and error messages differ significantly.

```javascript
import { describe, it, before, after, mock } from 'node:test';
import assert from 'node:assert/strict';

// Jest equivalent: expect(value).toBe(expected)
assert.strictEqual(actual, expected);

// Jest equivalent: expect(value).toEqual(expected) — deep comparison
assert.deepStrictEqual({ a: 1, b: [2] }, { a: 1, b: [2] });

// Jest equivalent: expect(fn).toThrow()
assert.throws(() => {
  throw new Error('boom');
}, { message: 'boom' });

// Jest equivalent: expect(fn).rejects.toThrow()
await assert.rejects(
  async () => { throw new Error('async boom'); },
  { message: 'async boom' }
);

// GOTCHA: assert.equal (non-strict) uses == not ===
assert.equal(1, '1');       // PASSES! Uses ==
assert.strictEqual(1, '1'); // FAILS! Uses ===
// Always import from 'node:assert/strict'!

// Mocking (Node.js 22+)
describe('fetch tests', () => {
  it('mocks fetch', async (t) => {
    const mockFetch = t.mock.fn(() => 
      Promise.resolve({ ok: true, json: () => Promise.resolve({ id: 1 }) })
    );
    // t.mock is scoped to the test — auto-cleaned up
  });
});
```

Always use `node:assert/strict` not `node:assert` to avoid loose equality surprises. The test runner supports `describe/it`, mocking, timers, and snapshot testing.

When you register a handler for SIGTERM or SIGINT, Node.js no longer exits automatically on that signal. Your handler must call `process.exit()` after cleanup.

```javascript
// WRONG — process never exits!
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  console.log('Received SIGTERM');
  // ... cleanup ...
  // Process continues running forever!
});

// CORRECT — exit after cleanup
process.on('SIGTERM', async () => {
  console.log('SIGTERM received. Shutting down gracefully...');

  // Close server to stop accepting new connections
  server.close(() => {
    console.log('HTTP server closed');
  });

  // Close database connections
  await db.disconnect();

  // Close Redis
  await redis.quit();

  console.log('Cleanup complete');
  process.exit(0); // MUST call this!
});

// GOTCHA: SIGINT (Ctrl+C) has the same behavior
process.on('SIGINT', () => {
  console.log('Ctrl+C pressed');
  process.exit(0);
});

// GOTCHA: SIGKILL cannot be caught — process is killed immediately
// You cannot handle SIGKILL

// GOTCHA: unhandled promise rejections during shutdown
// Add a timeout to force exit if cleanup hangs
process.on('SIGTERM', () => {
  const forceExitTimeout = setTimeout(() => {
    console.error('Forced exit after timeout');
    process.exit(1);
  }, 10000); // 10 second deadline
  forceExitTimeout.unref(); // Don't keep process alive for this timer

  // ... cleanup ...
  process.exit(0);
});
```

Always call `process.exit()` at the end of signal handlers. Add a force-exit timeout to prevent hanging during cleanup.

A single synchronous CPU-intensive operation blocks the entire event loop, preventing all I/O, timers, and HTTP requests from being processed.

```javascript
import { createServer } from 'node:http';

const server = createServer((req, res) => {
  if (req.url === '/cpu-heavy') {
    // BLOCKS entire server for ~5 seconds
    // No other requests are processed during this time!
    let result = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < 1e9; i++) result += Math.random();
    res.end(String(result));
  } else {
    res.end('OK'); // This handler is starved while /cpu-heavy runs
  }
});

// Fix 1: Use worker threads for CPU-heavy work
import { Worker } from 'node:worker_threads';

function cpuHeavy() {
  return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
    const worker = new Worker(
      new URL('./cpu-worker.js', import.meta.url)
    );
    worker.on('message', resolve);
    worker.on('error', reject);
  });
}

// Fix 2: Break up work with setImmediate
async function processLargeArray(items) {
  const results = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
    results.push(processItem(items[i]));
    // Yield to event loop every 100 items
    if (i % 100 === 0) {
      await new Promise(resolve => setImmediate(resolve));
    }
  }
  return results;
}

// Fix 3: Use AbortController for timeouts
const ac = new AbortController();
setTimeout(() => ac.abort(), 5000);
```

Never run CPU-intensive code on the main thread of a server. Use worker threads, break work into chunks with `setImmediate`, or offload to a job queue.

Adding event listeners without removing them is the most common source of memory leaks in Node.js. The `MaxListenersExceededWarning` is a symptom, not the root cause.

```javascript
import { EventEmitter } from 'node:events';

// MEMORY LEAK — listener added every request but never removed
const emitter = new EventEmitter();

function handleRequest(req, res) {
  // This adds a NEW listener on every request!
  emitter.on('update', (data) => {
    res.write(JSON.stringify(data)); // res may already be closed
  });
}

// Warning: MaxListenersExceededWarning: Possible EventEmitter memory leak detected.
// 11 update listeners added to [EventEmitter].

// CORRECT — remove listener when done
function handleRequest(req, res) {
  const handler = (data) => res.write(JSON.stringify(data));
  emitter.on('update', handler);

  req.on('close', () => {
    emitter.removeListener('update', handler); // Clean up!
  });
}

// BETTER — use once() or AbortSignal
function handleRequest(req, res) {
  const ac = new AbortController();

  emitter.on('update', (data) => {
    res.write(JSON.stringify(data));
  }, { signal: ac.signal }); // Auto-removed when signal aborts

  req.on('close', () => ac.abort());
}

// Detect leaks:
import { getHeapStatistics } from 'node:v8';
const { used_heap_size } = getHeapStatistics();
console.log(`Heap: ${(used_heap_size / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`);

// Track listener counts:
console.log(emitter.listenerCount('update'));
```

Always pair `on()` with a cleanup mechanism. Use `{ signal }` option or `once()` for auto-cleanup. Monitor `listenerCount()` in production.

Each worker in the Node.js cluster module is a separate process with its own memory space. They don't share variables, connections, or in-memory caches.

```javascript
import cluster from 'node:cluster';
import { cpus } from 'node:os';
import { createServer } from 'node:http';

if (cluster.isPrimary) {
  const numWorkers = cpus().length;
  console.log(`Primary ${process.pid} forking ${numWorkers} workers`);

  for (let i = 0; i < numWorkers; i++) {
    cluster.fork();
  }

  cluster.on('exit', (worker, code) => {
    console.log(`Worker ${worker.process.pid} died (${code}). Restarting...`);
    cluster.fork(); // Auto-restart crashed workers
  });
} else {
  // GOTCHA: each worker has its OWN in-memory state
  const cache = new Map(); // NOT shared between workers!
  let requestCount = 0;    // Each worker has its own counter!

  const server = createServer((req, res) => {
    requestCount++;
    // requestCount is per-worker, not total
    res.end(`Worker ${process.pid} handled ${requestCount} requests`);
  });

  server.listen(3000);
  // GOTCHA: all workers listen on same port — OS distributes connections
}

// For shared state, use:
// 1. Redis (most common)
// 2. IPC messages between primary and workers
cluster.workers[1]?.send({ type: 'cache-invalidate', key: 'user:123' });
// 3. SharedArrayBuffer (limited to numeric data)
```

Use Redis or a database for shared state across cluster workers. IPC messages work for coordination but add latency.

Node.js 22 changed JSON import assertions from `assert { type: 'json' }` to `with { type: 'json' }`. The old syntax is deprecated.

```javascript
// OLD (Node.js 20, deprecated in 22)
import data from './data.json' assert { type: 'json' };
// Warning: Import assertions are deprecated. Use import attributes instead.

// NEW (Node.js 22+)
import data from './data.json' with { type: 'json' };

// Dynamic import also uses 'with'
const config = await import('./config.json', { with: { type: 'json' } });

// GOTCHA: not all bundlers support 'with' yet
// Vite, esbuild may still need 'assert'
// TypeScript 5.3+ supports 'with' (import attributes)

// If you need to support multiple Node versions:
import { createRequire } from 'node:module';
const require = createRequire(import.meta.url);
const pkg = require('./package.json'); // Works everywhere

// Or use fs:
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
const config2 = JSON.parse(await readFile('./config.json', 'utf-8'));
```

Use `with` syntax for Node.js 22+. For cross-version compatibility, use `createRequire` or `fs.readFile`. TypeScript 5.3+ supports the `with` keyword.

`stream.pipe()` does not propagate errors — if the source stream errors, the destination is not automatically destroyed. Use `pipeline()` instead.

```javascript
import { createReadStream, createWriteStream } from 'node:fs';
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';
import { Transform } from 'node:stream';

// WRONG — errors not propagated, destination not cleaned up
const src = createReadStream('input.txt');
const dest = createWriteStream('output.txt');
src.pipe(dest);
// If src errors, dest is NOT destroyed — file handle leaks!
// If dest errors, src continues reading — waste of resources!

// CORRECT — pipeline handles everything
try {
  await pipeline(
    createReadStream('input.txt'),
    new Transform({
      transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
        callback(null, chunk.toString().toUpperCase());
      },
    }),
    createWriteStream('output.txt')
  );
  console.log('Pipeline complete');
} catch (err) {
  // All streams are destroyed automatically on error
  console.error('Pipeline failed:', err);
}

// With AbortSignal for cancellation
const ac = new AbortController();
setTimeout(() => ac.abort(), 5000); // Cancel after 5s

await pipeline(source, transform, destination, { signal: ac.signal });
```

Always use `pipeline()` from `node:stream/promises`. It handles error propagation, stream destruction, and supports AbortSignal for cancellation.

In ESM, timer functions like `setTimeout` are globals but `setImmediate` and timer utilities need explicit import from `node:timers` or `node:timers/promises`.

```javascript
// setTimeout, setInterval, clearTimeout, clearInterval are globals
// They work without import in both CJS and ESM

// But the promise-based versions must be imported
import { setTimeout as sleep } from 'node:timers/promises';

// Sleep for 1 second — no wrapper needed!
await sleep(1000);

// With AbortSignal for cancellation
const ac = new AbortController();
try {
  await sleep(5000, 'result', { signal: ac.signal });
} catch (e) {
  if (e.code === 'ABORT_ERR') console.log('Timer cancelled');
}

// setInterval as async iterator!
import { setInterval } from 'node:timers/promises';

const ac2 = new AbortController();
setTimeout(() => ac2.abort(), 10000); // Stop after 10s

for await (const _ of setInterval(1000, null, { signal: ac2.signal })) {
  console.log('Tick', new Date().toISOString());
  // Runs every 1 second for 10 seconds
}

// GOTCHA: setImmediate is not available in all environments
// It's a Node.js-specific API, not in browsers
import { setImmediate } from 'node:timers/promises';
await setImmediate(); // Yield to event loop
```

The `node:timers/promises` module provides `setTimeout`, `setInterval`, and `setImmediate` as promise-based APIs with AbortSignal support.

Since Node.js 15, unhandled promise rejections throw and terminate the process (exit code 1). This catches many developers who relied on the old warning-only behavior.

```javascript
// This will CRASH the process!
async function fetchData() {
  const res = await fetch('https://nonexistent.example.com');
  return res.json();
}
fetchData(); // Unhandled rejection → process crash

// GOTCHA: even forgotten .catch() on non-async code
Promise.reject(new Error('oops')); // Process crash!

// Handle globally as last resort
process.on('unhandledRejection', (reason, promise) => {
  console.error('Unhandled Rejection:', reason);
  // Log, report to error tracking, then exit gracefully
  process.exit(1); // Still exit — unhandled rejections indicate bugs
});

// GOTCHA: async event handlers can hide rejections
import { EventEmitter } from 'node:events';
const emitter = new EventEmitter();

// If this handler throws, it's an unhandled rejection
emitter.on('data', async (data) => {
  await processData(data); // If this throws → unhandled rejection!
});

// Fix: wrap async handlers
emitter.on('data', async (data) => {
  try {
    await processData(data);
  } catch (e) {
    console.error('Handler error:', e);
  }
});

// In Node.js 22, you can configure the behavior:
// node --unhandled-rejections=warn app.js  (old behavior)
// node --unhandled-rejections=throw app.js (default)
```

Always handle promise rejections. Use try/catch in async functions and .catch() on standalone promises. The crash is a feature — it surfaces bugs early.

Top-level `await` in ES modules blocks the execution of the module and any modules that import it. This can cause unexpected delays in application startup.

```javascript
// config.js
const response = await fetch('https://api.example.com/config');
export const config = await response.json();
// This entire module blocks until fetch resolves!

// app.js
import { config } from './config.js'; // Blocks here until config.js finishes
import { logger } from './logger.js';   // Also blocked waiting for config.js!

console.log('App started'); // Only runs after ALL imports resolve

// GOTCHA: circular dependency with top-level await can deadlock
// a.js: import { b } from './b.js'; await something;
// b.js: import { a } from './a.js'; await something;
// → Deadlock!

// Better pattern: lazy initialization
// config.js
let _config;
export async function getConfig() {
  if (!_config) {
    const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/config');
    _config = await res.json();
  }
  return _config;
}

// app.js
import { getConfig } from './config.js'; // Import is instant
const config = await getConfig(); // Await only when needed
```

Avoid top-level await for slow operations like network requests or database connections. Use lazy initialization patterns instead.

Creating a Readable stream from an async iterator using `Readable.from()` can lose backpressure when the consumer is slow, because the iterator keeps pulling data.

```javascript
import { Readable } from 'node:stream';

// Async generator that produces data fast
async function* generateData() {
  for (let i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {
    yield Buffer.alloc(1024, 'x'); // 1KB per chunk
  }
}

// GOTCHA: Readable.from() respects backpressure BUT
// if you consume it incorrectly, you lose it
const stream = Readable.from(generateData());

// WRONG — 'data' event disables backpressure (flowing mode)
stream.on('data', (chunk) => {
  slowProcess(chunk); // Data piles up in memory!
});

// CORRECT — use pipe or pipeline (paused mode with backpressure)
import { pipeline } from 'node:stream/promises';

await pipeline(
  Readable.from(generateData()),
  async function* (source) {
    for await (const chunk of source) {
      yield await slowProcess(chunk); // Backpressure respected!
    }
  },
  destination
);

// CORRECT — use for-await-of (automatically handles backpressure)
for await (const chunk of stream) {
  await slowProcess(chunk); // Each await pauses reading
}
```

Use `pipeline()` or `for await...of` to consume streams with proper backpressure. Avoid the `'data'` event unless you handle pausing manually.

`Buffer.from(string)` defaults to UTF-8 encoding. If your data is in Latin-1 (ISO-8859-1) or another encoding, you'll get corrupted data.

```javascript
// Default is UTF-8
const buf = Buffer.from('café');
console.log(buf.length); // 5 (é is 2 bytes in UTF-8)

// Latin-1: each character is exactly 1 byte
const buf2 = Buffer.from('café', 'latin1');
console.log(buf2.length); // 4 (é is 1 byte in Latin-1)

// GOTCHA: converting between encodings incorrectly
const binaryData = Buffer.from([0xFF, 0xFE, 0xFD]);
const str = binaryData.toString('utf-8'); // Corrupted! These aren't valid UTF-8
const str2 = binaryData.toString('latin1'); // Correct for binary-safe string

// GOTCHA: base64 encoding/decoding
const encoded = Buffer.from('Hello World').toString('base64');
// 'SGVsbG8gV29ybGQ='

const decoded = Buffer.from(encoded, 'base64').toString('utf-8');
// 'Hello World'

// GOTCHA: Buffer.from() vs new Buffer() — security
// Buffer.from() is safe: always creates a new buffer
// Buffer.allocUnsafe() is fast but contains OLD MEMORY DATA
const unsafe = Buffer.allocUnsafe(100); // May contain sensitive data from other operations!
const safe = Buffer.alloc(100); // Zero-filled, safe

// GOTCHA: Buffer.from(arrayBuffer) shares memory
const ab = new ArrayBuffer(8);
const buf3 = Buffer.from(ab); // Shares memory with ab!
buf3[0] = 42;
new Uint8Array(ab)[0]; // 42 — modified through shared memory
```

Always specify encoding explicitly. Use `Buffer.alloc()` over `Buffer.allocUnsafe()` unless you immediately fill the buffer.

Node.js 22's built-in fetch follows redirects by default but will NOT follow a redirect from HTTPS to HTTP. This is a security feature that can silently fail.

```javascript
// Server redirects: https://api.example.com → http://api.internal/data

const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data');
// res.status might be 200 but from the redirect target
// OR it might error if redirect goes HTTPS → HTTP

// GOTCHA: redirect modes
const res2 = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  redirect: 'follow',  // Default: follow redirects (up to 20)
  // redirect: 'error', // Throw on any redirect
  // redirect: 'manual', // Don't follow, return redirect response
});

// Manual redirect handling
const res3 = await fetch('https://api.example.com/data', {
  redirect: 'manual',
});
if (res3.status === 301 || res3.status === 302) {
  const location = res3.headers.get('location');
  console.log('Redirect to:', location);
  // Decide whether to follow based on your security policy
}

// GOTCHA: cookies are NOT sent on cross-origin redirects by default
// GOTCHA: POST body is dropped on 301/302 redirect (method changes to GET)
const res4 = await fetch('https://api.example.com/submit', {
  method: 'POST',
  body: JSON.stringify({ data: 'value' }),
});
// If server returns 301, fetch converts POST → GET and drops body!
// Use 307/308 redirects to preserve method and body
```

Be aware of redirect behavior: HTTPS downgrade is blocked, POST becomes GET on 301/302, and cookies don't cross origins.

Running `node --test --watch` re-runs ALL test files when any file changes, not just the affected tests. This can be slow for large test suites.

```bash
# Watch mode — re-runs ALL tests on any change
node --test --watch src/**/*.test.js

# GOTCHA: glob patterns may not work on all shells
# Use explicit paths or a test config
node --test --watch 'src/tests/*.test.js'

# Run specific test file only
node --test src/tests/user.test.js

# Filter by test name
node --test --test-name-pattern='user creation' src/tests/*.test.js
```

```javascript
// Filtering with describe/it
import { describe, it } from 'node:test';

describe('User', () => {
  it('should create user', () => { /* ... */ });
  it('should delete user', () => { /* ... */ });
});

// node --test --test-name-pattern='should create' runs only matching tests

// GOTCHA: test runner output formats
// Default is TAP (Test Anything Protocol)
// Use --test-reporter for different formats
// node --test --test-reporter=spec  (human-readable)
// node --test --test-reporter=dot   (minimal)
// node --test --test-reporter=junit (CI/CD)

// GOTCHA: coverage requires --experimental-test-coverage
// node --test --experimental-test-coverage
// Reports line/branch/function coverage in TAP output
```

For faster feedback in watch mode, organize tests into small files. Use `--test-name-pattern` to run specific tests during development.

`process.exit()` terminates the process immediately, before pending async operations, timers, or I/O callbacks complete. This can cause data loss.

```javascript
import { writeFile } from 'node:fs/promises';

// WRONG — file may not be written!
await writeFile('log.txt', 'important data');
console.log('File written');

process.exit(0); // Exits before flush completes!
// 'log.txt' might be empty or partially written

// CORRECT — let the event loop drain naturally
await writeFile('log.txt', 'important data');
console.log('File written');
// Don't call process.exit() — process exits when event loop is empty

// If you must exit with a code:
process.exitCode = 1; // Set exit code without forcing immediate exit
// Process will exit with code 1 when event loop drains

// GOTCHA: 'exit' event handler is synchronous only
process.on('exit', (code) => {
  // Cannot use async operations here!
  await writeFile('final.txt', 'data'); // DOES NOT WORK
  console.log('Exiting with code:', code); // This works (sync)
});

// For cleanup, use 'beforeExit' (fires when event loop is empty)
process.on('beforeExit', async (code) => {
  // Async operations work here!
  await flushLogs();
  await closeConnections();
  // But don't add new work or it loops forever
});
```

Prefer `process.exitCode` over `process.exit()`. Use `beforeExit` for async cleanup. The `exit` event only supports synchronous code.

Node.js has its own `AbortController` implementation. While similar to the DOM version, there are subtle differences in event handling and timeout behavior.

```javascript
// Basic usage — same as DOM
const controller = new AbortController();
const { signal } = controller;

// Pass to fetch
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com', { signal });

// Cancel after timeout
setTimeout(() => controller.abort(), 5000);

// Node.js specific: AbortSignal.timeout() — built-in timeout signal
const res2 = await fetch('https://api.example.com', {
  signal: AbortSignal.timeout(5000), // Throws after 5 seconds
});

// Node.js 22: AbortSignal.any() — abort when ANY signal fires
const userCancel = new AbortController();
const combined = AbortSignal.any([
  userCancel.signal,
  AbortSignal.timeout(30000),
]);
// Aborts on user cancel OR timeout — whichever comes first

// GOTCHA: abort reason
controller.abort('User cancelled'); // Can pass a reason
signal.reason; // 'User cancelled'

// GOTCHA: AbortError handling
try {
  await fetch(url, { signal });
} catch (e) {
  if (e.name === 'AbortError') {
    console.log('Request was cancelled:', signal.reason);
  } else {
    throw e; // Re-throw non-abort errors
  }
}

// GOTCHA: signal listeners should use { once: true } to avoid leaks
signal.addEventListener('abort', () => cleanup(), { once: true });
```

Use `AbortSignal.timeout()` for simple timeouts and `AbortSignal.any()` for combining cancellation sources. Always check `e.name === 'AbortError'` when catching.

`import.meta.resolve()` in Node.js 22 is synchronous, returning a string directly. In earlier versions and some other runtimes, it was async and returned a Promise.

```javascript
// Node.js 22 — synchronous
const resolved = import.meta.resolve('express');
console.log(resolved); // 'file:///node_modules/express/index.js'

// Relative resolution
const local = import.meta.resolve('./utils.js');
console.log(local); // 'file:///project/src/utils.js'

// GOTCHA: returns a URL string, not a file path
// import.meta.resolve('./config.json')
// Returns: 'file:///project/config.json'
// NOT: '/project/config.json'

// To get a file path:
import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url';
const filePath = fileURLToPath(import.meta.resolve('./config.json'));
// '/project/config.json'

// GOTCHA: older Node.js versions (20, 21) - async
// const resolved = await import.meta.resolve('express');
// In Node 22, this still works but the await is unnecessary

// Use case: find package.json location
const pkgUrl = import.meta.resolve('express/package.json');
const pkgPath = fileURLToPath(pkgUrl);
```

In Node.js 22, `import.meta.resolve()` is synchronous and returns a `file://` URL string. Use `fileURLToPath()` to convert to a filesystem path.

This error occurs when Node.js ESM resolver can't find a module. Unlike CommonJS, ESM does not try adding file extensions or looking for index files.

```
Error [ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND]: Cannot find module '/project/src/utils' imported from /project/src/index.js
Did you mean to import "./utils.js"?
```

```javascript
// WRONG — missing file extension
import { helper } from './utils';
// Error: Cannot find module '/project/src/utils'

// FIX — add .js extension
import { helper } from './utils.js';

// WRONG — directory import without index
import { config } from './config';
// Error: Cannot find module '/project/src/config'

// FIX — explicit index file
import { config } from './config/index.js';

// GOTCHA: TypeScript compiled to ESM
// Source: import { foo } from './foo.ts' ← WRONG
// Source: import { foo } from './foo.js' ← CORRECT (references compiled output)

// GOTCHA: package not found in node_modules
import express from 'express';
// Error: Cannot find module 'express'
// Fix: npm install express
// Or check package.json "exports" field blocks the subpath
```

ESM resolution in Node.js is strict: always include file extensions for relative imports, and reference `.js` for compiled TypeScript.

This error occurs when you `require()` a package that has `"type": "module"` in its package.json. The package is ESM-only and cannot be loaded with CommonJS `require()`.

```
Error [ERR_REQUIRE_ESM]: require() of ES Module /node_modules/got/dist/source/index.js
not supported. Instead change the require to a dynamic import()
```

```javascript
// WRONG — requiring an ESM-only package from CJS
const got = require('got'); // Error!

// Fix 1: Use dynamic import (works in CJS)
const got = await import('got'); // Returns a module namespace
const { got: gotFn } = await import('got');

// Fix 2: Convert your project to ESM
// Add to package.json: { "type": "module" }
// Then: import got from 'got';

// Fix 3: Use an older version that ships CJS
// npm install got@11 (last CJS version of got)

// Common ESM-only packages (must use import, not require):
// got, node-fetch (v3+), chalk (v5+), execa (v6+), p-limit (v4+)
// strip-ansi (v7+), globby (v13+), ora (v6+), del (v7+)

// GOTCHA: dynamic import() in CJS returns the module namespace
const module = await import('chalk');
// module.default is the default export
// module.red, module.blue etc. are named exports
```

Many popular npm packages have gone ESM-only. Options: use `import()`, downgrade the package, or migrate your project to ESM.

This error occurs when you try to import a subpath from a package that isn't listed in the package's `exports` field.

```
Error [ERR_PACKAGE_PATH_NOT_EXPORTED]: Package subpath './dist/utils' is not
defined by "exports" in /node_modules/some-package/package.json
```

```javascript
// The package only exports specific paths:
// node_modules/some-package/package.json
// { "exports": { ".": "./dist/index.js" } }

// WRONG — subpath not exported
import { util } from 'some-package/dist/utils';
// Error: Package subpath './dist/utils' is not defined by "exports"

// The only allowed import:
import { something } from 'some-package'; // Maps to ./dist/index.js

// Common occurrence with @mui/material:
import Button from '@mui/material/Button'; // Works (exported)
import { unstable_ClassNameGenerator } from '@mui/material/utils'; // May not work

// Fix 1: Check the package's exports field
// Look at node_modules/package/package.json for allowed subpaths

// Fix 2: Import from the main entry
import { utils } from 'some-package';

// Fix 3: Use createRequire to bypass exports (last resort)
import { createRequire } from 'node:module';
const require = createRequire(import.meta.url);
const util = require('some-package/dist/utils'); // CJS bypasses exports
```

The `exports` field is an intentional restriction by the package author. Check the package's documentation for supported import paths.

This error means another process (or a previous instance that didn't shut down properly) is already listening on the port.

```
Error: listen EADDRINUSE: address already in use :::3000
```

```javascript
import { createServer } from 'node:http';

const server = createServer((req, res) => res.end('OK'));

server.listen(3000).on('error', (err) => {
  if (err.code === 'EADDRINUSE') {
    console.error('Port 3000 is already in use!');
    // Option 1: try another port
    server.listen(0); // OS assigns a random available port
    // Option 2: find and kill the blocking process
    console.log('Run: lsof -i :3000 | grep LISTEN');
    process.exit(1);
  }
});

// Get the actual port (useful with port 0)
server.on('listening', () => {
  const { port } = server.address();
  console.log(`Server running on port ${port}`);
});
```

```bash
# Find what's using the port
lsof -i :3000
# or
ss -tulpn | grep 3000

# Kill the process
kill -9 <PID>

# Or use npx to find and kill
npx kill-port 3000
```

Common causes: previous process didn't shut down (use SIGTERM handlers), multiple dev servers running, or another application using the same port. Use port `0` for automatic assignment in tests.

Node.js has a default heap size limit (~1.5-2GB depending on the system). Large data processing, memory leaks, or unbounded caching causes this crash.

```
FATAL ERROR: CALL_AND_RETRY_LAST Allocation failed - JavaScript heap out of memory

<--- Last few GCs --->
[12345:0x...] 12345 ms: Mark-sweep 1396.2 (1422.5) -> 1396.1 (1422.5) MB
```

```bash
# Increase heap size (temporary fix)
node --max-old-space-size=4096 app.js  # 4GB
NODE_OPTIONS='--max-old-space-size=4096' node app.js

# For npm scripts:
NODE_OPTIONS='--max-old-space-size=4096' npm run build
```

```javascript
// Common causes:

// 1. Reading entire large file into memory
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
const data = await readFile('10gb-file.csv', 'utf-8'); // OOM!
// Fix: use streams
import { createReadStream } from 'node:fs';
import { createInterface } from 'node:readline';
const rl = createInterface({ input: createReadStream('10gb-file.csv') });
for await (const line of rl) {
  processLine(line); // Process line by line
}

// 2. Unbounded cache/array growth
const cache = new Map();
function processRequest(id, data) {
  cache.set(id, data); // Grows forever!
}
// Fix: use LRU cache with size limit

// 3. Monitoring memory usage
const usage = process.memoryUsage();
console.log({
  rss: `${(usage.rss / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,        // Total memory
  heap: `${(usage.heapUsed / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`,   // JS heap
  external: `${(usage.external / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1)}MB`, // C++ objects
});

// 4. Generate heap snapshot for debugging
import v8 from 'node:v8';
v8.writeHeapSnapshot(); // Creates a .heapsnapshot file
// Open in Chrome DevTools → Memory tab
```

Don't just increase the heap — find the leak. Use `--inspect` with Chrome DevTools Memory profiler or `process.memoryUsage()` to track growth.

Node.js 22 requires import attributes when importing JSON files in ES modules. Without them, the import fails.

```
TypeError [ERR_IMPORT_ATTRIBUTE_MISSING]: Module "file:///project/config.json"
needs an import attribute of "type: json"
```

```javascript
// WRONG — missing import attribute
import config from './config.json';
// TypeError: needs an import attribute of "type: json"

// CORRECT — Node.js 22+
import config from './config.json' with { type: 'json' };

// Dynamic import with attributes
const { default: pkg } = await import('./package.json', {
  with: { type: 'json' },
});

// GOTCHA: the error message may say "assertion" in older Node.js
// Node 20: assert { type: 'json' }
// Node 22: with { type: 'json' }

// Alternative: avoid import attributes entirely
import { readFileSync } from 'node:fs';
const config2 = JSON.parse(readFileSync('./config.json', 'utf-8'));

// Or use createRequire
import { createRequire } from 'node:module';
const require = createRequire(import.meta.url);
const config3 = require('./config.json');
```

JSON imports in ESM require the `with { type: 'json' }` attribute in Node.js 22+. Use `readFileSync + JSON.parse` for maximum compatibility.

This error occurs when Node.js doesn't have the OS-level permission to perform a file operation, or when a file is locked by another process.

```
Error: EPERM: operation not permitted, open '/etc/shadow'
```

```javascript
import { readFile, writeFile, chmod, access, constants } from 'node:fs/promises';

// Check permissions before accessing
try {
  await access('/path/to/file', constants.R_OK | constants.W_OK);
  console.log('File is readable and writable');
} catch {
  console.log('No access to file');
}

// GOTCHA: Windows file locking
// On Windows, files open by another process can't be deleted/renamed
try {
  await writeFile('locked-file.txt', 'new content');
} catch (err) {
  if (err.code === 'EPERM' || err.code === 'EBUSY') {
    console.error('File is locked by another process');
  }
}

// GOTCHA: Node.js permission model
// node --experimental-permission --allow-fs-read=/app app.js
try {
  await readFile('/etc/passwd');
} catch (err) {
  // Error: Access to this API has been restricted
  // ERR_ACCESS_DENIED (not EPERM) when using Node.js permissions
}

// Fix file permissions:
await chmod('/path/to/file', 0o644); // rw-r--r--
await chmod('/path/to/script', 0o755); // rwxr-xr-x

// Run with elevated permissions (not recommended):
// sudo node app.js
// Better: fix file ownership
// chown node:node /path/to/file
```

Check file permissions with `access()` before operations. On Windows, EPERM often means file locking. On Linux/macOS, it's usually OS-level permissions.

This warning fires when more than 10 listeners are added to a single event. It usually indicates a memory leak from listeners not being cleaned up.

```
(node:12345) MaxListenersExceededWarning: Possible EventEmitter memory leak detected.
11 error listeners added to [Server]. MaxListeners is 10.
Use emitter.setMaxListeners() to increase limit
```

```javascript
import { EventEmitter } from 'node:events';

// WRONG — adding listener in a loop/request handler
const emitter = new EventEmitter();

function handleRequest() {
  emitter.on('data', handler); // New listener on EVERY request!
  // After 11 requests → warning
}

// Fix 1: Remove listener when done
function handleRequest() {
  emitter.on('data', handler);
  // Later:
  emitter.off('data', handler);
}

// Fix 2: Use once() for one-time listeners
emitter.once('data', handler);

// Fix 3: Use AbortSignal (Node.js 22+)
function handleRequest() {
  const ac = new AbortController();
  emitter.on('data', handler, { signal: ac.signal });
  // When request ends:
  ac.abort(); // Automatically removes the listener
}

// If you genuinely need many listeners (rare):
emitter.setMaxListeners(50); // Increase limit
emitter.setMaxListeners(0);  // Unlimited (dangerous!)

// Debug: find where listeners are added
console.log(emitter.listenerCount('data'));
console.log(emitter.listeners('data')); // Array of handler functions

// Global: trace listener additions
emitter.on('newListener', (event, listener) => {
  console.log(`New '${event}' listener added. Count: ${emitter.listenerCount(event) + 1}`);
  console.trace(); // Stack trace shows where it was added
});
```

This warning is almost always a bug. Fix the leak rather than increasing the limit. Use the `newListener` event with `console.trace()` to find the source.

This error occurs when you try to send a response (headers or body) after the response has already been sent. Common in Express/HTTP handlers with multiple code paths.

```
Error [ERR_HTTP_HEADERS_SENT]: Cannot set headers after they are sent to the client
```

```javascript
import express from 'express';
const app = express();

// WRONG — two responses sent
app.get('/user/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.getUser(req.params.id);
  if (!user) {
    res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' });
    // Missing return! Code continues...
  }
  res.json(user); // Error: headers already sent!
});

// FIX — return after sending response
app.get('/user/:id', async (req, res) => {
  const user = await db.getUser(req.params.id);
  if (!user) {
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not found' }); // return!
  }
  return res.json(user);
});

// GOTCHA: middleware calling next() AND sending response
function authMiddleware(req, res, next) {
  if (!req.headers.authorization) {
    res.status(401).json({ error: 'Unauthorized' });
    next(); // WRONG — also calls next, which may send another response
    // Fix: don't call next() when sending a response
    return;
  }
  next();
}

// GOTCHA: error in async handler after response sent
app.get('/data', async (req, res) => {
  res.json({ data: 'initial' });
  await someCleanup(); // If this throws after response sent → crash
});

// Check if response was already sent:
if (!res.headersSent) {
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Server error' });
}
```

Always `return` after `res.send/json/end` in branching code. Check `res.headersSent` in error handlers. Never call `next()` after sending a response.

This error occurs when a file path is incorrect, but a subtle cause is using wrong path separators or not resolving relative paths correctly.

```
Error: ENOENT: no such file or directory, open './data/../config.json'
```

```javascript
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';
import { join, resolve, normalize } from 'node:path';

// WRONG — relative path depends on cwd, not file location
await readFile('./config.json'); // Relative to process.cwd()!
// If you run: node src/app.js from project root
// It looks for: ./config.json (project root)
// Not: ./src/config.json

// CORRECT — resolve relative to current file
import { fileURLToPath } from 'node:url';
const __dirname = fileURLToPath(new URL('.', import.meta.url));
const configPath = join(__dirname, 'config.json');
await readFile(configPath);

// Node.js 22+
const configPath2 = join(import.meta.dirname, 'config.json');

// GOTCHA: path.join vs string concatenation
const bad = __dirname + '/config.json';  // Might double-slash
const good = join(__dirname, 'config.json'); // Handles separators

// GOTCHA: Windows vs Unix paths
// Windows: C:\\Users\\app\\config.json
// Unix: /Users/app/config.json
// Always use path.join() — handles both

// Verify file exists before reading
import { access, constants } from 'node:fs/promises';
try {
  await access(configPath, constants.F_OK);
} catch {
  console.error(`File not found: ${configPath}`);
}
```

Always use `path.join()` or `path.resolve()` for file paths. Resolve relative paths from `import.meta.dirname` (Node.js 22+) not from `process.cwd()`.

These errors mean the remote server (or a proxy) closed the TCP connection unexpectedly. Common in long-running connections and keep-alive scenarios.

```
Error: read ECONNRESET
Error: socket hang up
Error: Client network socket disconnected before secure TLS connection was established
```

```javascript
// With fetch:
try {
  const res = await fetch('https://unstable-api.example.com/data', {
    signal: AbortSignal.timeout(10000), // 10s timeout
  });
} catch (e) {
  if (e.cause?.code === 'ECONNRESET') {
    console.log('Server closed connection — retrying...');
  }
}

// With http module:
import http from 'node:http';

const agent = new http.Agent({
  keepAlive: true,
  keepAliveMsecs: 30000,
  maxSockets: 50,
  timeout: 60000,
});

// GOTCHA: keep-alive connections can go stale
// Server closes after idle timeout, but client doesn't know
// Next request on that socket → ECONNRESET

// Fix: handle connection reset with retry
async function fetchWithRetry(url, retries = 3) {
  for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
    try {
      return await fetch(url);
    } catch (e) {
      const isRetryable = ['ECONNRESET', 'ETIMEDOUT', 'ECONNREFUSED', 'UND_ERR_SOCKET']
        .some(code => e.message?.includes(code) || e.cause?.code === code);
      if (!isRetryable || i === retries - 1) throw e;
      await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1000 * (i + 1)));
    }
  }
}

// GOTCHA: AWS ALB/ELB has 60s idle timeout by default
// If your keep-alive is > 60s, you'll get ECONNRESET
// Set keep-alive timeout LESS than the load balancer timeout
```

ECONNRESET is usually transient. Implement retry logic for idempotent requests. Set keep-alive timeouts shorter than your load balancer's idle timeout.

This error means you're using `import` syntax in a file that Node.js treats as CommonJS (the default).

```
SyntaxError: Cannot use import statement outside a module
```

```javascript
// This file is treated as CJS by default
import express from 'express'; // SyntaxError!

// Fix 1: Add "type": "module" to package.json
// { "type": "module" } — makes ALL .js files ESM

// Fix 2: Use .mjs extension
// Rename file to app.mjs — treated as ESM regardless of package.json

// Fix 3: Use require() (stay in CJS)
const express = require('express');

// GOTCHA: "type": "module" affects ALL .js files in the package
// If you need some files as CJS, use .cjs extension
// script.cjs — always treated as CommonJS
// script.mjs — always treated as ESM
// script.js  — depends on nearest package.json "type" field

// GOTCHA: Jest, ts-node may not support ESM by default
// Jest: set in jest.config.js:
// { transform: {}, extensionsToTreatAsEsm: ['.ts'] }

// GOTCHA: config files (jest.config.js, webpack.config.js)
// may need to be .cjs if your project is "type": "module"
// jest.config.cjs, webpack.config.cjs
```

Set `"type": "module"` in package.json for ESM, or use `.mjs`/`.cjs` extensions. Config files for tools may need `.cjs` extension.

The OS has a limit on the number of file descriptors a process can have open simultaneously. High-concurrency file operations can hit this limit.

```
Error: EMFILE: too many open files, open '/path/to/file'
```

```bash
# Check current limit
ulimit -n  # Default is often 1024

# Increase temporarily (current shell)
ulimit -n 65536

# Increase permanently (macOS)
sudo launchctl limit maxfiles 65536 200000

# Increase permanently (Linux)
# Add to /etc/security/limits.conf:
# * soft nofile 65536
# * hard nofile 65536
```

```javascript
// WRONG — opens thousands of files simultaneously
import { readFile } from 'node:fs/promises';

const files = getThousandsOfFiles();
const results = await Promise.all(
  files.map(f => readFile(f, 'utf-8')) // Opens ALL files at once!
);

// CORRECT — limit concurrency
async function asyncPool(items, concurrency, fn) {
  const results = [];
  let i = 0;
  async function worker() {
    while (i < items.length) {
      const index = i++;
      results[index] = await fn(items[index]);
    }
  }
  await Promise.all(Array.from({ length: concurrency }, worker));
  return results;
}

const results2 = await asyncPool(files, 50, (f) => readFile(f, 'utf-8'));

// Or use graceful-fs which queues operations
import gracefulFs from 'graceful-fs';
// Drop-in replacement that retries on EMFILE
```

Limit concurrent file operations to 50-100. Use `graceful-fs` as a drop-in replacement that handles EMFILE automatically, or implement your own concurrency pool.

This error often occurs when the default export from a CommonJS module isn't what you expect. CJS modules expose their exports differently than ESM.

```
TypeError: express is not a function
TypeError: (0 , _express.default) is not a function
```

```javascript
// CommonJS module (express):
// module.exports = function createApplication() { ... }

// In ESM, CJS module.exports becomes the default export
import express from 'express'; // express is the function ✓

// But some CJS modules have a different structure:
// module.exports = { createApp, helper }
import pkg from 'some-cjs-lib';
pkg.createApp(); // Access via the default import

// GOTCHA: named imports from CJS may or may not work
import { createApp } from 'some-cjs-lib'; // May fail!
// Node.js tries to detect named exports from CJS but it's not always reliable

// Fix: destructure from default import
import pkg from 'some-cjs-lib';
const { createApp, helper } = pkg;

// GOTCHA: module.exports = class or module.exports = function
// These become the default export directly
import MyClass from 'cjs-class-lib';
new MyClass(); // Works

// But: exports.MyClass = class
// This becomes: { default: { MyClass: class } }
import pkg from 'cjs-class-lib';
new pkg.MyClass(); // Access through default

// Debug: inspect what you're importing
import * as all from 'some-cjs-lib';
console.log(Object.keys(all)); // See available exports
console.log(typeof all.default); // Check default export type
```

When importing CJS from ESM: use default import and destructure. Named imports from CJS are unreliable. Check the module's actual exports structure.

ECONNREFUSED means the connection was actively refused — nothing is listening on the target port, or a firewall is blocking it.

```
Error: connect ECONNREFUSED 127.0.0.1:5432
Error: connect ECONNREFUSED ::1:3000
```

```javascript
// Common causes and fixes:

// 1. Service not started yet (race condition in startup)
import { setTimeout } from 'node:timers/promises';

async function waitForService(url, maxRetries = 30) {
  for (let i = 0; i < maxRetries; i++) {
    try {
      await fetch(url);
      return; // Service is ready
    } catch (e) {
      if (e.cause?.code !== 'ECONNREFUSED') throw e;
      await setTimeout(1000); // Wait 1 second between retries
    }
  }
  throw new Error(`Service at ${url} not available after ${maxRetries} retries`);
}

// 2. IPv4 vs IPv6 mismatch
// 'localhost' may resolve to ::1 (IPv6) but service listens on 127.0.0.1 (IPv4)
// Fix: use 127.0.0.1 explicitly, or make server listen on '0.0.0.0'
server.listen(3000, '0.0.0.0'); // Listens on all interfaces

// 3. Docker networking
// 'localhost' inside Docker doesn't reach the host
// Use host.docker.internal on Mac/Windows
// Use --network host on Linux

// 4. Environment-specific URLs
const dbUrl = process.env.DATABASE_URL || 'postgresql://localhost:5432/mydb';
// In CI/Docker, DATABASE_URL should point to the correct host
```

Common causes: service not running, IPv4/IPv6 mismatch (use `127.0.0.1` not `localhost`), Docker networking, or wrong port.

This error differs from ERR_MODULE_NOT_FOUND — it specifically means the package directory exists but Node.js can't resolve the entry point.

```
